title: Glass clamp and heat bed for Mini Kossel

description.text: Recently I built a heat bed for my Mini Kossel printer. The heat bed was built based on parate project. I used 1mm aluminium only on top and other "layers" was cut from laminate (1mm thick) and 2mm cork.

Heat insulation

M3 screws used to mount the bed are insulated in order to prevent heat transfer - from top I printed a PET-G washer (bed_wahser.stl), and a screw holes, which is 6mm in diameter, are insulated by bowden used for 3mm filament (OD: 6mm ID 4mm).

Heat bed parts

I created also 3D models of bed parts which are cut from laminate

  • base.stl
  • ring.stl

This is what is provided in parate project but there is no STL format which was usefull for me.

Glass clamps

On aluminium surface I put a round glass (170mm diameter). After print is finished I like to take out a glass and then remove printed object. This is very convenient.

I designed glass clamps (clamp.stl) which

  • holds tight glass on place
  • it is easy to put and remove glass

Note: clamps fits only original Mini Kossel design base on 15x15 OpenBeam profiles.

description.text:
I designed this cam for my quadcopter, the Crossfire 2.
The Pi Zero has a video-out, so the idea was, to have a live picture and to record Full-HD-Video at the same time. Of course you can use the cam without a copter too.

How it works:

POWER-ON -
Switch the cam on and the Pi will boot and start the actioncam, indicated by lighting up the status-LED.
VIDEO -
Push Button short, this switches on the prewiew (for FPV) and starts recording video
Push again to stop record
TIMELAPSE -
Push button for at least a second - this starts the prewies (for FPV) and beginns to catpture pictures every 3 seconds. Push Buton again to stop.
SHUTDOWN -
Push Button longer than 5 seconds. The Pi will shut down. Wait a few more seconds after the status-LED goes out, before you switch the Pi off.

Assembly:
You have to solder the components. Look for the read-me and the code on git.hub to see which ports/pins on the raspberry are used for push-button and status-led.
I used a little breadboard to solder both, button and led. There are guides in the lid, that hold the board when assembled.

https://github.com/willie42/pi-actioncam

On github you´ll find the python3 code for the cam itself and a shell script to convert the video into a common format (mp4).

Partlist:
Rasperry Pi Zero
Rasperry Cam (V1.3 or 2.0)
Push-Button
small Switch
standard 3mm LED (and/with resistor)
Lipo 1s min. 500 mAh
Power Boost 5v / Lipo-Charge-Module
Nano Wifi- or Blutooth-adapter to get the films/pictures of the camera

UPDATE 26.03.17: I will not continue to work on it. While testing I had massive frame drops. This and limitation to 5M when using live video-out made me decide to buy a runcam2 for my crossfire quadcopter.

title: Simple Handheld ActionCam/ Camera Gimbal Grip 2D or 3D Hand Held

description.text:
This is a simple gimbal grip for Action Cams, smartphones and regular cameras. You can print the parts for the most simple version, including a battery case and the holder for the gimbal, or you can add the parts for a switch, a joystick and different gimbals. This thing has the following parts:

Battery case:

  • BattCase - the lower part of the battery case, holding a 3S Lipo battery
  • BattCapSimple - a simple version of the battery cap, providing space for the cables and a screw
  • BattCapSwitch - a battery cap with space for a switch to turn on and off the gimbal
  • BattCapWithJsNdSwitch - a battery cap with space for a switch to turn on and off the gimbal and for a joystick to move the camera in the gimbal
  • ToSmartphone - a small plate to attach a smartphone to the grip, using this Smartphone Tripod holder. Then, use the Smartphone to control the camera.

Gimbal part:

  • Walkera-G2D-Mount - a plate to easily mount the Walkera G-2D gimbal on
  • Sizable 2D Gimbal for YOUR camera

What you also need:

  • Lipo 3S battery, and a charger for it
  • Selfie Stick for Action Cams with a 1/4" nut in its bottom
  • 1/4" long screw to attach the battery holder to the Selfie Stick
  • 1/4" short screw to attach a smartphone to the grip
  • Cable from battery to gimbal - 4-Pin JST-XH 2.5mm to JST BEC 3mm - you will have to solder or crimp this
  • Gimbal, e.g. Walkera G-2D Gimbal
  • Optionally a 12V lighted toggle switch
  • Optionally a "rocker gimbal joystick"

See the photos for these parts, and the HowTo.pdf on how to assemble everything.

For the joystick cap...

The battery cap for switch and joystick has two support sticks in its inside, which simplify printing. You can easily break these out after printing.

description.text:
The Pi Palette is a Raspberry Pi 3 single board computer in a 3D printed enclosure to disguise it as a (somewhat chunky) makeup palette.

•Full BOM is not in the files list- includes TaoBao link to mirrored glasses for those who asked:-)

•As shown the Pi Palette is running Kali Linux - a pentesting (hacking) distribution, but you can run several other Linux versions- and even a version of Windows 10. Just please remember that every time you run Windows on hardware fully compatible with Linux a baby penguin dies.

•Wireless charging, and a 5000mah battery which seems to be good for at least a few hours depending (the backlit screen can be turned off separately while bruteforcing, wardriving and other headless tasks)

•An RTL3070 WiFi adapter which can be swapped out for a Software Defined Radio without losing basic WiFi connectivity due to the rPi3s onboard WiFi.

•A 5in, 800x480 "smart mirror" type display in portrait orientation with optional touchscreen capability.

•Makeup trays can be 3D printed to accommodate most major brands of cosmetic pots.

Lots of people have asked me where I got the portrait layout keyboard. Here's the current situation:

There is no consistently produced version of the RF mini keyboard. I spoke to iPassport and they just make a batch when someone meet their MOQ. See: http://www.chinaimportal.com/blog/minimum-order-quantity-moq-why-it-s-required-by-chinese-suppliers/

The current version of the Pi-Palette shown uses a iPazzPort/Unisen KP-810-02 (http://ipazzport.com/en_productinfo.asp?id=152) it's not available in the West, but is in China:

https://item.taobao.com/item.htm?id=537262357094

Because of this I've made alternate files for both the bottom half and the keyboard cover so you can also use the iPazzPort/Unisen KP-810-05E, KP-810-05V, KP-810-05C:

KP-810-05E http://ipazzport.com/en_productinfo.asp?id=153
KP-810-05V http://ipazzport.com/en_productinfo.asp?id=159
KP-810-05C http://ipazzport.com/en_productinfo.asp?id=154

So you have a total of four keyboard options depending on what's available where you are. Updated STL files are labeled accordingly.

description.text:
Improved Schilt for snow pole waster.

After the first training session one of the V1 wasters broke at the point where the crossbar rod went through. The hole for the crossbar rod and the hole to fixate the rod with a screw made that point too weak for light to average drills.

improvements:

*holes to fixate two separate crossbar rods on either side of the snow pole. No need to bore an 8 mm hole.

*holes to fixate the schilt on the snow pole with short screws.

*center hole for the snow pole is a bit bigger so the bending of the pole don't cause stress on the layers and risk them to crack.

description.text:
This replacement spool holder for the Hephestos 2 has two rolls attached to ball bearings for the filament spool to sit and run on. The whole assembly fits snugly on the Hephestos 2's frame, right where the stock spool holder attaches. This design proofed to run way more quiet than the stock one for me, and also allows for a smoother unrolling of the spool during print jobs thanks to the easy going rolls.

To build this you'll need to print:

  • 2 x spoolholder_roll.stl, with support from platform
  • 4 x spoolholder_rollend.stl
  • 4 x spoolholder_washer.stl

  • 1 x spoolholder_bar.stl
  • 1 x spoolholder_bar_filamentguide.stl (or if you don't want to use the filament guide another spoolholder_bar.stl)

Or just:

  • 1 x spoolholder_plate.stl, with support from platform (should fit nicely on the bed of the Hephestos 2)

Additionally you'll need:

  • 4 x 625ZZ ball bearings
  • 4 x M5x16mm screws (e.g. DIN 912)
  • 4 x M5 hex nuts (e.g. DIN 934)
  • 4 x M3x10mm screws (e.g. DIN 912)

If you need to make any adjustments, you can find the Fusion360 files here.

Notes:

You only need support for the two rolls, due to the pockets for the bearings. All other parts should print just fine without supports.

I printed all parts in orange PLA, with two perimeters.

Exploded view

See the exploded view for assembly instructions. Attempt at a textual description follows ;)

  • Attach one ball bearing each to the upper larger holes in the two sides. To do this push one M5 screw through the hole, put the washer on it, put the bearing on it, then secure with an M5 nut. Make sure to mirror the assemble for one side.
  • Attach the roll end pieces on both sides of each roll, with the flange facing outside. It should be a snug press fit. If it isn't you might want to secure things with a bit of super glue.
  • Plug the rolls onto the ball bearing assemblies.
  • Put the two bars between the sides where the 3mm holes are located, screw them together with the M3 screws (it should work just screwing into the plastic). This should make the whole assembly fairly rigid.
  • Slide on top of your Hephestos 2's frame.

description.text:
Here is a small stellated dodecahedron with a hole in one pyramid that serves as a point for hanging.  Two related polyhedra are also included.  
The method of construction replaces each face of a dodecahedron with scaleable pentagonal pyramids.  The right choice of scale factor gives a small stellated dodecahedron.  Another known polyhedron, the Catalan solid called the pentakis dodecahedron, can also be constructed.  
The two additional polyhedra included here are composed of 60 approximately equilateral triangles, one a stellated form, the other an indented form.  
See the openSCAD code.
A raft and external support is required when printing the stl files.  A scad file which animates the change between the forms is included.

To create these, I used coloring book motifs that I converted into vector format. For this I used the free software Incscape but any vector graphics program works fine.
Google "character name coloring pages" to find suitable pictures to work with.

  1. Save the picture you want and import it into Incscape.
  2. In incscape, create a bitmap copy of the object.
  3. Trace the lines of the bitmap. Use threshold 0,0 to get thicker lines. Simpler pictures works best, you don't want crazy amouts of detail since the 3D printer most likely will not be able to print it properly anyway. Some cleanup of the picture might be required to get it right for 3D printing. Make sure the outer edge is solid.
  4. Save as DXF or SVG format. This might depend on wich CAD-program you're using.
  5. Open the file in your CAD-program. Add the picture to a sketch and create your cookie cutter. Experiment to find what's working best for your setup.

I was excited when Philips finally came out with an affordable switch for its lighting but disappointed that I could not find some way to mount the switches in-box. Here is a 3D-printed caddy to hold the switch (use 1/2" magnets in the recesses to hold the switch in place) and a file to use in a laser cutter to modify a (Leviton) switch plate. I used a two-gang box to mount the switch next to a toggle (which actually controls power to the bulbs, just in case the IoT gods aren't smiling at any particular time), but I'm sure you could remix this design for any other configuration.

The second version of the caddy (RemoteHolderV2.stl) has posts which sit in the screw locations on the switchplate, and a post that sits into the bottom mounting ear on the electrical box (I used to have one on the top ear, too, but it interferes with the bump on the back of the dimmer remote). Screwing the plate down from the other side provides a compression fit. This won't work if you're using a single gang box. (This is the version shown in the second and third pictures.)

The first version of the caddy (RemoteHolder.stl) needs to be epoxied into the switch plate. There are some benefits to this; the little bump in the back of the Hue remote interferes with the mounting ear on a standard electrical box and this preparation seems to avoid it better. This version also keeps screw holes clear, so you could use a #6 screw with a small head to hold the plate in place. (This is the version shown in the first and fourth pictures.)
